text.tspan: The visualization was done within the JHAV server-client framework
JHAV was chosen for its empasis on user engagment
We provide the user default values but allow them to generate the visualization by
entering their own numbers in either binary or decimal.
The input window will automatically convert between the bases for user convenience
erroneous input will auto-correct and provide the user feedback to the error

Constructivist theory of learning influenced our approach for our hypertextbook. We address the student's pre-existing knowledge and use that as the basis for teaching the algorithm.
Our research turned up few visualizations for the topic of binary multiplication in computer organization.
One at http://www.frontiernet.net/~prof_tcarr/Multiplication/applet.html allowed for step-by-step viewing and limited questions, but did not include discussion of hardware or signed values.
Others at http://www.ecs.umass.edu/ece/koren/arith/simulator/ inlcuded many algorithms and was linked to a (non-free) textbook, but did not support any levels of engagement beyond basic "Viewing".
We created two modules, an online text or hypertext resource and dynamic visualization of the algorithm
Our intent was to design the modules to work well together, but allow each to stand on its own.
We choose Booth's Multiplication Algorithm for its its versatility for allowing discussion of math and hardware.
Multiplication of signed numbers is not always taught in computer organization
Some textbooks do not provide any coverage
Those that do vary significantly in approach and method
Mathematic background and hardware implementation
details is not always both covered.
Time prohibitive for professors to develop this material
Limitations on classroom time may restrict adding new material

Format based on constructivist theory of learning by addressing what the students know and building on that
Begins with binary multiplication as repeated addition
Then the shift-and-add method of multiplication is introduced
Introduce hardware design issues which then leads to the simple binary multiplication method.
We then point out the problems with signed binary numbers
Booth's algorithm is introduced, along with a mathematical justification for why it works
We then adapt Booth's algorithm to hardware.
The textbook concludes with questions and exercises to test student's understanding, as well as a link to our visualization
